          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">China maritime movements</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-11-2.jpg" alt="China maritime movements" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Tensions between China and Taiwan have <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/taiwan-says-china-deploying-largest-naval-fleet-in-decades/a-71008022" target="_blank">escalated</a> significantly, as Taiwanâ€™s Defense Ministry reported the largest Chinese naval deployment near the island in nearly three decades. Over the past 24 hours, 47 Chinese military aircraft and 12 warships were detected, marking the highest military presence in months. The deployment is even more significant than the <a href="https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/3187774/beijings-war-games-taiwan-after-pelosis-trip-spark-concerns" target="_blank">2022 war games</a> triggered by former U.S. House Speaker Nancy Pelosiâ€™s visit. Taiwanese forces are on high alert. Defense Ministry officials described the Chinese navy as forming â€œtwo wallsâ€ in the Pacific, signaling an effort to frame the Taiwan Strait as Chinaâ€™s internal waters.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Relations have worsened following Taiwanese President Lai Ching-teâ€™s <a href="https://apnews.com/article/taiwan-us-china-lai-ching-te-hawaii-guam-7abcd0e5803fdb7f20615fd394aca91b" target="_blank">U.S. visit</a>, which Beijing condemned. China views Taiwan as part of its territory, while Taiwan asserts its sovereignty and relies on U.S. support for defense. Since Lai Ching-te took office, China has launched two large-scale military drills around Taiwan. â€‹</p>
        </mj-text>
