          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Trumpâ€™s peace commitment</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky <a href="https://www.france24.com/en/europe/20241210-zelensky-salutes-trump-s-strong-resolve-to-end-war-in-ukraine" target="_blank">expressed gratitude</a> for U.S. President-elect Donald Trump's commitment to ending the war in Ukraine. They <a href="https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/world/macron-trump-zelensky-hold-trilateral-on-sidelines-of-notre-dame-ceremony/ar-AA1vtsKy?ocid=BingNewsSerp" target="_blank">discussed</a> peace strategies in Paris with Macron, and Zelensky reiterated that ending the conflict is Ukraine's top priority. He thanked Macron for facilitating the discussions and acknowledged concerns over potential territorial concessions in Trump's promise for a quick resolution.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Trump called for an â€œ<a href="https://www.euronews.com/my-europe/2024/12/09/trump-urges-immediate-ceasefire-in-ukraine-and-suggests-nato-role-rethinking" target="_blank">immediate ceasefire</a>â€ and suggested Zelensky was ready to negotiate. Zelensky responded cautiously, <a href="https://kyivindependent.com/trump-zelensky-ready-to-make-a-deal-on-the-war-in-ukraine/" target="_blank">asserting</a> that a reliable peace requires more than symbolic agreements, as Russia has previously reignited conflicts. He stressed the need for guarantees to prevent further Ukrainian losses and rejected any compromise on Russian occupation.</p>
