          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is Taiwan's official status?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-11-3.jpg" alt="What is Taiwan's official status?" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Taiwanâ€™s status is a unique and complex issue in global politics. Officially known as the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Taiwan" target="_blank">Republic of China</a> (ROC), it operates as a self-governed democracy with its government, military, and economy. However, China views Taiwan as part of its territory under the â€œ<a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-38285354" target="_blank">One China</a>â€ policy, creating tension. As of 2024, only 12 countries officially recognize Taiwan as independent.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Taiwanâ€™s vibrant democracy and tech-driven economy make it a significant global player.â€‹</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Most countries, including the U.S., <a href="https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2024-01-13/biden-u-s-does-not-support-taiwan-independence" target="_blank">donâ€™t officially recognize</a> Taiwan as separate but maintain informal relations and support its defense. This delicate balancing act aims to avoid provoking China while supporting Taiwanâ€™s autonomy. Most of the International community prefers the status quo for these reasons. Taiwan wants complete independence and recognition, and China wants to hold on to the â€œOne Chinaâ€ policy. Many Taiwanese still favor the <a href="https://globalaffairs.org/research/public-opinion-survey/americans-and-taiwanese-favor-status-quo" target="_blank">status quo</a>, as a change could result in a full-on war.â€‹</p>
             <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">For many people in Taiwan, their <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2024/01/16/most-people-in-taiwan-see-themselves-as-primarily-taiwanese-few-say-theyre-primarily-chinese/" target="_blank">identity</a> leans increasingly toward being â€œTaiwaneseâ€ rather than â€œChinese,â€ reflecting their distinct culture and political system. Although most of the population is ethnically Han Chinese, Taiwan has a smaller <a href="https://www.bbc.com/travel/article/20240125-a-vibrant-celebration-of-taiwans-little-known-original-inhabitants" target="_blank">indigenous population</a> of 16 <a href="https://taiwan.gov.tw/content_2.php" target="_blank">recognized</a> indigenous tribes.â€‹</p>
        </mj-text>
